\f0\fs24 \cf0 VirtualGL is an open source package which gives any Unix or Linux remote display software (remote X11, VNC, NX, etc.) the ability to run OpenGL applications with full 3D hardware acceleration and direct rendering.  When an OpenGL application is run with VirtualGL on a Unix or Linux server, VirtualGL intercepts a handful of GLX calls from the application and modifies them so that 3D rendering will occur in an invisible pixel buffer (Pbuffer) on a 3D accelerator card located in the server machine.  As each frame is rendered on the server, VirtualGL reads back the pixels and sends them through one of several "image transports".  The simplest of these (the X11 Transport) re-composites the image into the appropriate X window, and this can be used to give hardware-accelerated 3D capabilities to VNC or other X proxies.  In a LAN environment, VirtualGL can also send the 3D images through its built-in high-speed motion-JPEG image delivery system (the VGL Transport) and re-composite them on a remote X server.\
